ce:section.ce:para:
The DOS spectra of nano-carriers and their complexes with PA have been computed and are displayed in Fig. 6
                        . The form of the PA drug’s DOS curve changes substantially after adsorption on the nano-carrier surfaces, whereas the nano-carriers DOS curve changes minimally [57–60] (Fig. 7
                        ).

To account for the reactivity of the nano-carriers, chemical descriptors of the PA drug and their complexes are determined (Table 3
                        ). The chemical potential of the nano-carriers is increased when the PA drug is adsorbed on the nano-carrier surfaces except for coronene. Adsorption of PA drug decreases the hardness value of CC nano-carrier, while adsorption on the NN-P and BB-P surface causes only an increase in the hardness value and no significant change for BN-O adsorption. The electrophilicity index has a low value (1.9398 eV), indicating that the PA molecule is stable. The electrophilicity index value for all decreases following PA drug adsorption except for BN-P adsorption. Overall the simulations show that PA drug adsorption on nano-carriers improves chemical stability [65]. The FMOs plot of pristine nano-surfaces and PA adsorbed nano-surfaces are shown in Fig. 4. For CC, the electron density is not seen along with the axial C atoms (HOMO and in LUMO); For BB-P, HOMO is mainly on the B atom containing the center ring while LUMO is absent in carbon atoms at the center ring; For NN-P, HOMO density is throughout the molecule and no electron density is seen along with the N, N containing axis for LUMO; Electron density of LUMO is absent in B atom in BN-O and HOMO is absent in N atom of BN-P (Fig. S2). In all PA molecule adsorbed complexes, HOMO is over the PA molecule and LUMO is over the nano-surface showing maximum charge transfer and adsorption process (Fig. 4). The Mulliken charges of atoms of PA molecule before and after adsorption are given in the Table S1 in which there are changes for charge values of PA molecule which are near to the nano-surfaces; O5, O19, H6, and H20 atoms for CC-PA and BN-O-PA systems and N9 O7, H8, H
                        10, and H
                        11 for the other systems (Table 4
                        ).
